<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/vs/articles/index.php'>Marvel VS</option><option value='/heroclix/articles/articles.php'>HeroClix</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magic/articles/articles.php'>Video Games and Movies</option><option value='/wars/articles/articles.php'>Wizards Minis</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> The 20 Greatest and Most Influencial Players in LOTR History<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(5.00)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=11045'>Patrick "Patrick M. S" Sullivan</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=11045&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> November 17, 2006</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> The 20 Greatest and Most Influencial Players in LOTR History<br />
<br />
<br />
With the recent surge of Top 20 SW :CCG Players of all time appearing on Decktech as of late, I thought it would be only fitting to make one for LOTR. This is by no means official since it’s completely biased on my interpretation of what makes a great and influential player. Plus, some potentially great and influential players such as Simon Schebben won’t make this list since I’ve only seen him play once. Luckily I’ve met almost all the top LOTR players and seen them play a few times during my run at the game. I hope this makes for an enjoyable read and if your name got dropped in this article, then congratulations. You’ll all that and a bag of chips. <br />
<br />
Before getting to the list, lemme just quickly mention the honourable three who JUST missed the top 20. In 21st place, Dominic Gaudreault. Dominic knocked me out immediately in Day Three of the first ever World Championships and has always been a force to be reckoned with in any competitive game he plays. Unfortunately he has one of the strongest tendencies to go on tilt once he makes a play that he considers sub-optimal. I think this detracted from some of the greatness that Dom could have achieved at this game. Still $1,625 in total winnings and some monstrous Day One PSE finishes are nothing to sneeze at. <br />
<br />
Finishing right behind Dom in a tie for 22nd place are Will Cruse and myself. I consider Will to be my greatest equal in this game. I found our styles to be very similiar and I really enjoyed his disposition in and out of the game. I wish I got to see more of Will during my run at the game since I don’t expect to make it to Alabama anytime soon. I’ll always remember Will ordering vodka straight up in an irish pub during Origins with me. Good times. Will earned a total of $575 during his run and I think my highlight with him was our final match during Day One of the Open format World Championship qualifier in  2003. <br />
<br />
As for me, I really do consider Will, Dom and the following 20 people to be better than me at the game. I made a decent $3,300 during my run at the game with my most « notable » finish being 1st during the 2005 N.A. Continentals. I had a good time with the game but I don’t think I ever really played to win and it showed. The following 20, to me, are truly la creme de la creme in very many different ways. So here we go! (oh, and beside each name I’ll put where they’re from and how much they made during their run at LOTR). <br />
<br />
<br />
20. Peter Sundholm (Washington, USA) $1,050<br />
<br />
Mullet-head himself. Although his biggest finish was only 3rd during San Diego’s ComicCon PSE in 2002, I do consider Peter one of the greatest and more influential players of LOTR. He’s either the oldest or second-oldest to make the list, but he showed that you can have fun and still place very highly. Cutthroat is not a word in this man’s vocabulary. I had the pleasure of having my butt handed to me in Spokane’s DPC in 2004 (or so) by Peter who had built a fairly impressive deck to completely demolish Rohan (he used Moria Archery to devastating effect). I think Peter is easily the best gentlemen of all LOTR players and a great sportsman. <br />
<br />
<br />
19. Matthew Yakobina (Quebec, Canada) $2,625<br />
<br />
Few people actually know what a ferocious competitor this 2002 DGMA Player of the Year was. Yako, like Dom, left the game before their time. Yako’s competitive field in Montreal was one of the toughest if not the toughest in the world. He had to deal with the Malboeuf brothers, Mike Lane, Marchi, Dom, Brochu and a ton of others in various local events and TOCs. And let me tell you, there was a time when Yako could NOT lose a single game. He was in the zone and understood the game at another level than most. He was impossible to defeat. It was really something else. His win at DragonCon PSE 2002 was the highlight of his stint at LOTR and I think he would have been much higher on this list if he had had the interest to stick around. Oh, and he’s a pretty great guy too. Decided to run GPN Weekend Montreal in the dead of winter long after his retirement from the game. I’m glad he continued to travel with us when he moved to Vs afterwards. <br />
<br />
<br />
18. Emir Delic (Michigan, USA) $17,000<br />
<br />
That’s a whole lot of money! Enough to buy plasma screens and that’s it. Emir has the misfortune of being labelled the Chris Moneymaker of LOTR since the DGMA decided to allow deck changes between Day Three and Four of the World Championships in 2004. This change thus did not reward consistency but rather who can built the better deck (one which can’t get screwed by teching). Josh had the misfortune of taking the very vulnerable Beseigers and Emir had the fortune of taking the perfect anti-Besieger deck, pure Elves with Galadriel, Lady Redeemed and lots of those cool Sauron-kill cards. <br />
<br />
Wait a minute… that’s until Emir delivers another knock out by placing 2nd in Day Two of the Origins PSE in 2005 thereby disproving the Chris Moneymaker ‘fluke’ label that was so hastily slapped on Emir’s large behind. So what we’re left with is actually a very decent player who showed EVERYONE that you don’t need to be a veteran LOTR player to win. Emir had only MONTHS of experience before winning worlds. Pretty impressive. It takes alot of character as well to not be put on tilt by Josh and Emir concentrated on his win like a seasoned competitor. And then beyond and above all of that, Emir is actually a real nice guy out of the game. I like-a dis man. <br />
<br />
<br />
17. Michael Ium (Ontario, Canada) $550<br />
<br />
Who?!<br />
<br />
Michael, like Emir, was another late starter with LOTR. But this was a guy who, when he commits himself to a game, is VERY hard to beat. Mike Ium puts a ridiculous amount of concentration towards a game and will very rarely make a sub-optimal move. Heck, in his first year of poker (post-LOTR), he banked over $100,000. That takes focus (it wasn’t all from one event). Josh keeps telling me that Mike also has one heck of a sense of humour but you gotta spend quite a bit of time with this guy to see it. Josh was right tho, it’s there. <br />
<br />
Anyway, I really do think that Mike was one of the best players at LOTR regardless of not placing highly on Day Twos. But this is a guy who CONSISTENTLY made Day Two’s (5 in all or so). <br />
 <br />
<br />
16. Brian Fred (Indiana, USA) $1,800<br />
<br />
Hips don’t lie. This guy was a heavyweight at LOTR. Brian had a fairly jovial presence at the table but make no mistake, this guy could eat you for breakfast in the game. I think Brian, like Dom, was another player who perhaps tilts too easily after making a mistake. Still, Brian was a solid LOTR player through and through. One of the regular players that instantly puts a smile on my face when I see him and his big cute mug.<br />
<br />
<br />
15. Mike « ILTC! » French (Washington, USA) $2,300<br />
<br />
I was thinking about including both French brothers together in one entry but if I did that, Ryan would have dragged Mike off the top 20 list and into the lower 80’s or so. So let’s just pretend that Ryan didn’t survive his birth or something and stick with the better of the two. <br />
<br />
Ah, Mike French. The quintesential love-him-or-hate-him player. I honestly could never understand what problems some people seem to take with this guy. I thought he had a great fun presence at the LOTR table and was an outstanding player. Although when he would think of a way to lose a certain game, it would often happen. And on the other hand, I know of no other player that takes risks in the game like Mike French does. This guy, along with Brochu, has made the sickest double moves I have ever seen in a face full of shadow. <br />
<br />
Although he only has one big win under his belt (Vegas PSE 2004), he’s been to Day Two PSEs three times. That’s pretty strong consistency considering, I think, there was only one PSE where he didn’t make Day Two that he played in (Origins 2003). I think Mike was a great LOTR player and a strong presence in the community. <br />
<br />
<br />
14. Martin Hechtberger (Austria) $2,250<br />
<br />
Ah, Martin. My hand-picked teammate during the 2004 World Cup. Remember when I put out applications to be the 3rd player on my qualified team? To sit alongside Ken Ellingsen and myself and play against the best in the world? It was a tough decision and some players came close to beating Martin (I remember Blumberg wanting to be on the team with his impressive 4th place finish in the 2004 Wonder Waters PSQ) but in the end, I had to pick this huge powerhouse of a player for Team Gondor, 2nd place 2004 World Cup finishers. <br />
<br />
Martin caught my interest online with his win of the 2004 Online PSI. I then looked back to see if he had any good finishes in the real life game and saw that he landed a 1st place finish in Day One of the Utretcht PSE. And let me tell you, the European PSEs are FAR harder than any U.S. PSE. The level of play there is sick. Plus they stall like CRAZY. For Martin to survive in that environment and also in the online field of mostly European players, i knew that this had to be one of the best players out there at the time. I ended up having to get an XXXL t-shirt for him but it all worked out. Martin is a terrific player and handles the pressure better than most. He’s also a real nice fella with his broken english and heavy Austrian accent. I remember being so happy finishing 2nd in the World Cup that I hugged him until it started to make me smell bad too. <br />
<br />
<br />
13. Brad Eier (Ohio, USA) $1,875<br />
<br />
Brad is another of the consistent players. He reminds me alot, gameplay wise, of Mike French. Except without Mike’s nasty tendency of turning wins into losses somehow. I don’t think Brad will ever forget his loss to Brochu at the 2004 Origins PSE due to Bold Men & Grim. But let’s go back one pairing where he ravaged one Patrick Sullivan playing a Dworc deck. Brad was playing Gondor-Elf and some shadow that I’m too lazy to dig up (let’s say Corsairs). I’m quite certain he was playing the exact same deck (almost card for card) that Mike French was playing one pairing earlier (against me). So here I am with the same match-up back to back. I managed to win against Mike in 3 games and you’d think my chances of beating Brad would be through the roof since I knew EXACTLY what to do and what not to do. But Brad played such an amazing game that I never had the chance. His discomfort with Morcs was just as strong as Mike’s but Brad never swayed and managed to take the win. Moments like this and many many others are what makes Brad Eier the People’s Champ (whatever the hell that means anyway). <br />
<br />
<br />
12. William Diniega (Colorado, USA) $525<br />
<br />
Now here we find one forgotten soul. I wonder if this will be my most controversal entry into the top 20. Well, either way, I think Will Diniega is one of the most seasoned players out there. This is like the Vietnam vet who did 3 or 4 tours of duty. Other than the 3rd place finish in the 2003 ComicCon PSE, there was no notable finishes for Will (although placing 7th in the first ever World Cup in Germany is pretty hawt). Still, I really think Will was one heck of a great and influential player. I think that perhaps, like me, Will wasn’t as focused on the winning but more on the having fun. Regardless of his record, his name was one you didn’t want to hear when your pairing was being announced. Unless of course, you just wanna laugh and don’t care about winning J<br />
<br />
<br />
11. Casey Barson (Utah, USA) $750<br />
<br />
This guy is probably a surprising entry into my top 20, especially so high, right? Well, maybe you didn’t play enough with Casey if you think so. Casey Barson was one of the sickest consistent players in LOTR in terms of making Day Two of PSEs and like events. Would you believe me if I told you that he made NINE Day Twos (I’m including Day Three of a World Championship here too)?! That’s alot, man. And Casey proved that you didn’t need a big budget to win at LOTR. Casey made some KILLER Moria decks for very cheap and was an excellent Moria player in the day (not as good as Malboeuf but good enough). Casey often never made it past the 1st bracket of a Day Two PSE but it was insane how many Day Twos he made (even finishing 1st on one Day One). He was a really good player with a good attitude and was not one that I wanted to be paired up against on Day One. <br />
<br />
<br />
and now the top ten!!<br />
<br />
<br />
10. Bernd Reinartz (Germany) $3,425<br />
<br />
Our first European player makes the list in tenth place. I got to meet Bernd during the 2004 World Cup where my Team lost to his in the finals. He was definately the powerhouse of that team and could simply not be beaten. I remember taking a mental note to watch out for this guy in the future. A pretty unfriendly character who’s all business during the game. And he should be cuz when he’s focused, he’s quite good. <br />
<br />
Fast forward 5 months or so and I fly back across the Atlantic to play in the European Continentals and PSE Utrecht. I’m rooting for my World Cup teammate, Kenneth Ellingsen in the finals of the PSE who’s up against Bernd. Bernd is totally dominated in terms of meta and this should be an easy win for Ellingsen. But Bernd not only plays the match-up perfectly but manages to slightly get inside Ken’s head and make him question some of his plays. I couldn’t believe Ken lost and I then knew that Bernd was definately slated to be one of the top players ever. <br />
<br />
<br />
9. Dan Clark (Michigan, USA) $1,250<br />
<br />
Ah Dan… Somehow Dan actually tops the charts for « person-I-most-want-to-see-at-conventions » when I’d go to the various cons around the States. Since Day One of seeing Dan is his big straw hat, I think he may have replaced Mike Girard as my favourite life size teddy bear (man, does that ever sound ghey). Not only is Dan cute as a button but he’s one heck of a player and deckbuilder. I think he single handedly figured out how to get Moria to totally wreck Dwarves using Blood Runs Chill. A very nice anti-tech with Plundered Armories (or whatever) and it worked like a charm. <br />
<br />
Like Casey Barson, Dan is another one of those awesome fantasy LOTR picks because he would almost ALWAYS make Day Two of a PSE if he was there. The only exception being 2005 PSE where he and I got nailed on massive decklist errors and it prevented him from making Day Two. If memory serves, he wrote it all with one of those Sharpies and filled it out fairly randomly putting cards like, « Sting, foil » and « Legolas, Greenleaf x5 » in a standard format deck. Hilarity at its best. Remember that John Murphy he used to hang around with? Well, I sure hope he’s dead. <br />
<br />
<br />
8. Alex Tennet (Pennsylvania? England? Who knows) $3,900<br />
<br />
For a guy who plays slow as molasses, here’s a guy who sure learned to master the game quick. The first World Championships he got 1st in his Day Two heat and stayed at the top of his bracket to make finals against Brochu where he lost but put up a great fight. Being the consistent player he is, he follows that strong finish up with winning the North American Continentals the year after. And perhaps most impressive of all, this is a player who consistently places near the top in both American and European events. <br />
<br />
Not only a terrific player but a genius deckbuilder as well. His Firebomb perfect swarm was simply the sickest swarm deck I had ever seen. At the Syracuse PSI in NY (which he won), he someone swarmed my 9-companion fellowship that single moved into site 7 with Aragorn, Ranger of the North and a ton of other healthy companions. Alex SWARMED that fellowship after taking 30 minutes in his shadow phase. But he did it. Amazing. <br />
<br />
<br />
7. Mathieu Brochu (Quebec, Canada) $26,500<br />
<br />
Yes, Brochu actually does have the highest winnings ever in LOTR ($2,250 more than Dalton). Brochu ties Dalton for most championship wins ever at 4 each (Brochu won the first World Championships, Origins PSE 2003,  World Cup 2003 and Origins PSE 2004). In fact, Brochu never made a Day Two PSE or Day Three Worlds that he DIDN’T win. He was definately a beast at Match Play. Capable of sizing up a match-up and figuring out how to win much easier than his opponents. I remember at Worlds 2002 after he defeated Tennet in the finals, some friend of Alex’s comes up to me and says, « your friend Brochu was lucky. » Yannick also tore the guy’s head off but I simply said, « We’ll see » and Brochu proved that he was no Chris Moneymaker (man, I love ragging on that guy). <br />
<br />
Brochu then moved on to other games and won ANOTHER car playing Anachronism (he won a PT cruiser during LOTR’s first Worlds, for those that forget). I’m not sure what he’s up to now but he truly was the Lord of the Rings…. (*barfs*)<br />
<br />
<br />
6. Kenneth Ellingsen (Norway) $4,325<br />
<br />
In the same way that Brochu could « see the code » in LOTR’s Matrix, I’m quite certain Kenneth Ellingsen has the same gift. A terrific deckbuilder and player, Kenneth knows how to almost instantly win a certain match-up, right from the get-go. This is why he most often plays decks of 60 cards with some sort of wicked cycling shadow or something, in order for him to get the cards he needs quickly. Ken, along with Michael Ium, were the two most consistent winners in the Online LOTR game as well. <br />
<br />
I was happy to share Ken as a teammate in our 2nd place finish at the 2004 World Cup after qualifying together at the PSE Vegas World Cup Qualifier (we had met before at two previous LOTR World Championships). We both lost a ton at Blackjack but we did win a good friendship (ugh.. who writes this stuff?). <br />
<br />
Anyway, basically anyone that can consistently place well in the European theatre is a strong player for sure. Ken won the Utretch PSE in 2004 and placed 2nd in both the 2005 European Continentals and Utretch PSE. It was actually pretty funny J<br />
<br />
<br />
5. Patrick « BadBeef » Malboeuf (Quebec, Canada) $8,800<br />
<br />
Haha, fooled you. I bet you thought I was gonna put this powerhorse as number one or two, right? I was tempted but I think his rightful place is here as number five. Pat never considered himself number one anyway. I remember the day he admitted to himself that Dalton was simply a better player than him. It was a pretty big moment for Pat and I think it’s good to know you’re not the best cuz then you can always improve. And this is something Pat was very big at. Improving himself. He’s lock himself in his apartment with his brother, David, and their friend David Marra-Hurtubise and they’d playtest for 3 full days. At the end of which, both Davids didn’t want to see another card ever again but Patrick was ready for another game. He took a very scientific approach to playtesting and really twisted each deck as much as possible to test for stress. Where does the deck have its pressure points? Pretty amazing stuff. <br />
<br />
I met Patrick right at the beginning and we were friends right off the start as we both brought alcohol to the evening tournaments in Montreal, much to the chagrin of the store owner at the time. Patrick had a huge influence on me aspiring to be a better player than I was and I’m glad he was present at all my early wins. He qualified for the first 2002 World Cup and placed 6th but learned enough about the meta to make a great deck to win the European PSE that same week. He then finished 3rd at Worlds that year and got 2nd for Player of the Year. Got 1st in the Toronto TOC the next year and got the title stripped away on a collusion charge (thus setting quite the example for others). Then he picks up his dropped books and papers and moves on to winning World Cup in 2003 along with a few other really high finishes in Europe and the States. If anyone remembers his Deck Clinic 101 on DGMA, they’ll realize how seriously Pat took the game. And don’t get me started on his Underdeeps of Moria deck. I don’t think I’m alone when I say that watching him play that thing was watching Tiger Woods getting an Albatross. It was just pure skill and I couldn’t fathom how to emulate it. A great player and a good friend. <br />
<br />
<br />
4. Benoit Lemaire (France) $3,100<br />
<br />
Who?! Yeah, that’s right, a Frenchman who didn’t fight poorly or surrender readily when faced with opposition. Like Sundholm, Benoit is one of the more aged players. Except instead of sporting a Fabio-esque mullet, Benoit chooses the balding eagle as his skull topping. <br />
<br />
Benoit is actually one of the most consistent players in the history of LOTR. From beginning of the game to the « end », he racked up many impressive finishes, including strong place finishes in 2003 and 2004 Worlds. I got to play against him at Worlds but I’ll never forget when my World Cup team had to fight against his in order to determine who gets to take on Bernd’s team in the finals. I choose Benoit as my adversary and he says in French, « Thanks, I would have chosen you as my first pick as well » and then he went on to destroy me with some choke Dwarf fellowship. With morcs most likely. <br />
<br />
Benoit proved that age does not matter in LOTR and was a real strong competitor right from the beginning and I defiantely think he’s earned his place as the 4th greatest of all time regardless if he’s less known in the States. <br />
<br />
<br />
3. Jonas Skali (Germany) $5,450<br />
<br />
Jonas is the single best European player and deckbuilder period. You think about how Dalton and Malboeuf dominated much of North America, well Jonas did the same thing in Europe. 2003 was definately Year of the Skali after Jonas wins two PSEs in Europe, placing 6th in the 3rd PSE of that year and places 4th in the World Cup as well. <br />
<br />
I believe at the time Dom and maybe Pat were working on decks with Jonas and the insight he gave was really something else. Anytime I made up some new deck, Dom would always tell me, « check with Jonas if its any good. » I finally met him near the end my run at LOTR. I think it was in Europe during World Cup or Continentals (I can’t remember) and I was amazed at how young he was. If Benoit can prove that the old guys have loaded guns, then Jonas did the same for the young crowd. I believe he was only 16 or so when he was dominating the European scene. Amazing player. <br />
<br />
<br />
2. Josh Cornwell-Mott (Ontario, Canada) $13,000<br />
<br />
Well, I suppose this may be my most controversal pick of them all. I put the biggest jerk of LOTR ever as the 2nd Greatest and Influential player?! Well I did and I stick by it. And I think it’s only fitting to put him in 2nd, since Josh came in 2nd so many times in so many big events (2003 Origins PSE, Vegas 2004 PSE, World Championships 2004). Love him or hate him, Josh was a heck of a consistent powerhorse (I need a thesaurus badly) at LOTR. <br />
<br />
The saddest thing about Josh’s run at LOTR is that he never had a solo big win on his own (I don’t consider the Michigan PSI to be a big big deal) and his World Cup win was shared with Brochu and Malboeuf. That must be the event that put Josh on various European hit lists. I got to play against Josh several times over the years and he was one of the most focused players there was. And agree with it or not as a viable strategy, NO ONE could get into your head and wreck your game like Josh could. <br />
<br />
If you never experienced it or witnessed it first hand, you have a really good opportunity to see it in action. There’s a poker player that I SWEAR not only kinda looks like Josh but totally acts like him in a few incidents that I’ve seen Josh get himself into. He’s called Eric Molina and he’s the biggest jerk I’ve ever seen at a poker table. This guy has Josh’s act down cold. I think they share some DNA. <br />
<br />
The saddest part of it is that Josh was the coolest guy out of the game ever. It was like Dr. Jekyll and Mr. Hyde all over again. But this article is on the in-game persona and that was one that was hard to beat. Josh was one of the only players that you’d actually have to consciously work at ignoring his antics if you didn’t want to lose any focus and make a mistake. And the results don’t lie, it must have worked some of the time since he had a really strong consistent record throughout his stay at LOTR. Last I hear he’s playing poker these days with Michael Ium and I hope he’s doing as well as Mike is. <br />
<br />
<br />
Which brings us to number and no surprise, it has to be :<br />
<br />
<br />
1.	Michael Dalton (New Jersey, USA) $24,250<br />
<br />
Yeah, he’s pretty good, I guess. <br />
<br />
Well, Mike definately takes the cake for most consistent player ever. And the funny thing is that he could play the same decks and strategies and consistently win with those as well. Right from the beginning, like Brochu, Mike was a very strong player. He won both the NYC and NJ TOCs in 2002 when he started playing and placed 2nd in the first PSE at Dragoncon. Even placed 7th in the Worlds that year. And this was BEFORE he started his run of wins at LOTR. Where Skali was dominating Europe in 2003, Dalton was tearing up North America like it was his job. Not including the PSQ and TOC he won that year, Mike started off the season well with a 6th place in the Origins PSE (somehow I managed to win that best-of-three match against him. I think it was one of the highlights of my time in LOTR), also that year he got 2nd in the Vegas PSE (learning what Dunland is), winning the San Diego PSE (and telling me to shush the whole time), winning DraconCon PSE (after finishing 20th or so on Day One) and also winning Worlds that year. What a beast! The next year, he wins the San Diego PSE again. <br />
<br />
What I like most about Dalton’s wins and why I consider him not only the greatest but also the most influential player in LOTR, is that he PROVED you can consistently win this game. Being « LOTR’d » was a term for n00bs and those that couldn’t blame themselves. You don’t hear poker pros answer « I got river’d » when asked why they lost the WSOP in any given year. Dalton showed that you can get above the drawing luck of the game and control your own skill and destiny to the point that you can win consistently at this game (and make some decent coin doing it). I think Dalton’s winning streak was one of the best things to happen to LOTR because it took out the idea that playing competitive LOTR was a crapshoot. <br />
<br />
Internet tough guy or not, Dalton was THE heavyweight champion of LOTR. None can deny it. I’d love to hear that friend of Tennet’s tell me that « Dalton got lucky » in 2003. <br />
<br />
-------<br />
<br />
Ok, well I guess that sums it up. Those, in my view, are the 20 greatest and most influential players of LOTR. I had a great 4 years with the game and these were the players that had the biggest effect on me and on people I know. Their contributions to the game and the gaming community cannot be denied. I’m glad to have known the twenty that raised the bar for the rest of us. <br />
